Now that the holiday season‘s been over and I’ve had more time to live with this shoot, I feel like it’s a good time to revisit it. 

Back in December, I had asked @coolin_mc if any of @wrteknica’s customers were willing to put a tree on their car for the Christmas project I was running. Not long after, Colin offered me two GT3 Cups for the occasion. I thought he was joking, and asked for 3. It was at that point that I learned to not call Colin’s bluffs. 

I had been saving the perfect spot just for this occasion. I personally have never seen a 991 Cup driving through mountain roads, much less on the snow, let alone 3 of them. You guys know me, I love contrast. 

I was happy to see @cooled.collective tag along too - creating with friends always offers more inspiration opportunities than not. We had to race against the sun, which always sets obscenely early in the mountains. 

In the end, this was a highlight of the year kind of shoot. I knew I had to revisit this shoot when I had more time to give it the attention it deserves.

On to the next 🫶

I usually don’t post film work on this page, but these are a little more experimental and fun to talk about. I call it my poor man’s XPan. 

These are “panoramic” medium format exposures from my Bronica ETRSi with a 135N film back modified to mimic a 135W (Zenza Bronica’s factory pano back for the ETR system). In less wordy terms, a medium format camera shooting 35mm film loaded into a film back with a masked film window. 

The results, while not perfect (notice the edges - I suspect it’s due to focal coverage not being accounted for since this is a modified 135N and Bronica’s 75mm was never meant to cover such a broad area with 120 film) are pretty great. There’s just something about medium format lenses creating wide scenes on 135. 

It’s a pain to load, and weirder to shoot. Per roll of film, you get 18 exposures instead of 36, because after each photo you take, you have to take a dark slide photo immediately after. If you dont, you get a double exposure overlap (see photo 2) due to the film advance having to compensate for a greater distance than its original 2:3 window. 

So it’s more expensive, more work, and more to carry. But it’s so worth it, in my opinion. Unfortunately the winding lever assembly broke and I’m still unsure where to source replacement parts for a niche back. 

As always, dev & scan by @lastgoodfilmlab 🤝

The holy grail of all things automotive, the F40 represents a moment in automotive history of perfect driving balance and tranquility. 

Some would say it’s even more significant than the splitting of the first atom or the discovery of fire. And, for the most part, those people would be correct. 

The F40 did what cars before it didn’t really get a good chance to have a good crack at. It gave you and I an absolutely unobtainable yet awkwardly believable goal to dream about.
